recommandationVideos.Title: The Israel-Palestine conflict: a brief, simple history
recommandationVideos.Description:
The conflict is really only 100 years old.

Subscribe to our channel! http://goo.gl/0bsAjO

One of the biggest myths about the Israel-Palestine conflict is that it's been going on for centuries, that this is all about ancient religious hatreds.

In fact, while religion is involved, the conflict is mostly about two groups of people who claim the same land. And it really only goes back about a century, to the early 1900s. At its heart, it is a conflict between two self-determination movements ‚Äî the Jewish Zionist project and the Palestinian nationalist project ‚Äî that lay claim to the same territory.

recommandationVideos.Title: The Israel-Palestine conflict: a brief, simple history
recommandationVideos.Description:
The conflict is really only 100 years old.

Subscribe to our channel! http://goo.gl/0bsAjO

One of the biggest myths about the Israel-Palestine conflict is that it's been going on for centuries, that this is all about ancient religious hatreds.

In fact, while religion is involved, the conflict is mostly about two groups of people who claim the same land. And it really only goes back about a century, to the early 1900s. At its heart, it is a conflict between two self-determination movements ‚Äî the Jewish Zionist project and the Palestinian nationalist project ‚Äî that lay claim to the same territory.

Read more about the Israel-Palestine conflict on Vox: http://bit.ly/2S7gFlT

recommandationVideos.Title: The Middle East's cold war, explained
recommandationVideos.Description:
How two feuding countries are tearing apart the Middle East.

Help us make more ambitious videos by joining the Vox Video Lab: http://bit.ly/video-lab

The Saudis and Iranians have never actually declared war on each other. Instead, they fight indirectly by supporting opposing sides in other countries and inciting conflicts. This is known as proxy warfare. 

And it‚Äôs had a devastating effect on the region. Countries, especially poor ones, can‚Äôt function if there are larger countries pulling strings within their borders. 

And that‚Äôs exactly what's happening in the Middle East. The Saudi-Iranian rivalry has become a fight over influence, and the whole region is a battlefield.

recommandationVideos.Title: ‚ÄòGrotesque‚Äô: Sky News host slams ‚Äòtopsy turvy‚Äô genocide accusations against Israel
recommandationVideos.Description:
Sky News host Chris Kenny has slammed South Africa‚Äôs ‚Äútopsy turvy‚Äù genocide accusation against Israel in the International Court of Justice as ‚Äúgrotesque‚Äù.

The African nation alleged Israel knew of the number of civilians it was killing and had shown an "incontrovertible" intent to commit genocide.

The United Nations court on Friday imposed temporary measures against Israel to ensure genocidal acts are not committed in Gaza but refused to call for a ceasefire.

Mr Kenny stressed the only way to protect innocent Palestinians and save Israeli hostages is for Hamas to lay down its arms.

‚ÄúLet's be clear, we should all be vitally concerned about the loss of innocent lives in Gaza,‚Äù he said.

‚ÄúNo matter that the numbers are unknown and no matter that Hamas has created the situation, and put innocent people's lives in danger, we all want the loss of innocent lives to stop immediately.

‚ÄúBut here's the thing; if that's what you want, then there is only one thing that your protests should call for.

‚ÄúThey should demand that Hamas lays down its arms and returns every single hostage being held now, before then surrendering its own leadership to Israel.‚Äù

recommandationVideos.Title: 'Worst Savagery Against Jews Since Holocaust' | Benjamin Netanyahu v Douglas Murray | Full Interview
recommandationVideos.Description:
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu sits down for an exclusive one-on-one interview with Douglas Murray on TalkTV to reveal that Israel will go it alone, if needs be, in order to secure its future.

Speaking to TalkTV for an exclusive half-hour interview, the Israeli Prime Minister says: ‚ÄúLook, you know this statement, ‚ÄòA man's got to do, what a man's gotta do?‚Äô Remember the days when you can actually say that? Well, today you say ‚ÄòA person has to do, what a person has to do, okay‚Äô. Well, let me extend that, ‚ÄòA nation has to do what it has to do to survive‚Äô. 

‚ÄúAnd if we have to take action both in the South and in the North, that is understood by many to be a just action‚Ä¶ but [if] they cannot stand the heat of public opinion, then we'll just have to do it alone. We will do what we need to do.‚Äù

Prime Minister Netanyahu told Douglas Murray that the October 7th attack on Israel, was "the worst savagery perpetrated against Jewish people since the Holocaust", and that he thought there was little difference between what Hamas 'savages' did compared to Hitler' Nazis.

The Prime Minister also gave his view of what would happen in Gaza once Hamas were defeated, saying demilitarisation in the area could only be handled by Israeli forces. And he opened up about the possibility of fighting in the north and the south, talking about the threat of Hezbollah and Iran.

He went on to say that beating Hamas would ‚Äútake some time‚Äù but that the conflict was wider than just Israel, warning the West: ‚ÄúIf Barbarism wins here, Europe will be next, America will be next.‚Äù

Netanyahu also branded freeing half of the Israeli hostages as a ‚Äúmajor achievement‚Äù - despite criticism from some quarters - and explained he didn‚Äôt care what his legacy was as long as Israel prospered.

recommandationVideos.Title: The rise and fall of the medieval Islamic Empire - Petra Sijpesteijn & Birte Kristiansen
recommandationVideos.Description:
Trace the rise and fall of the Islamic Empire, from the prophet Muhammad in the 7th century to the sacking of Baghdad. 

--

In the 7th century CE, the prophet Muhammad united the people of the Arabian Peninsula through the formation of Islam. Over the next 30 years, caliphs conquered vast areas beyond Arabia, including their mighty neighbors the Persians and Byzantines. But an empire this vast was at risk of conflict and fracture. Petra Sijpesteijn and Birte Kristiansen detail the rise and fall of the Islamic Empire.

Lesson by Petra Sijpesteijn & Birte Kristiansen, directed by Elahe Baloochi, Fardi Mahmoodi.
